jobs.title: Schoology LTI integration with a Video Platform company
jobs.description:
Requirements for Schoology:

1. As a Schoology admin, I can install an LTI app for our video platform
    1. Among of the 4 types of app (LTI 1.3, Standard App, Resource App, LTI 1.1), it's most likely we need to do **LTI 1.3**.
    2. Screencastify must be available in the Schoology App center
    3. I can add app to to my individual account or organization account.
    4. App must be visible in the left panel of Schoology Courses, ‘Add Materials’ and in the Content Editor plug-ins ‘Add-ons’.
2. **APP** Videos must be embeddable in the editor and assignments.
    1. Features that live on watch pages like questions and captions must also be supported on videos embedded in Schoology. 
        
        [Data on Interactive Questions Usage by accounts who use Schoology](https://www.notion.so/Data-on-Interactive-Questions-Usage-by-accounts-who-use-Schoology-37cee642fe18455d8c889d98cb754f1c?pvs=21)
        
        1. Create a separate page that is basically a fullscreen version of watch page, but only the video (without sidebars). **(What elements of watch page will a separate watch page have?)**
    2. If a watch page is deactivated due to freemium limitations, make the video unviewable in Schoology.
    3. We must be able to collect analytics on **APP**  videos viewed on Schoology and surface that information on **APP** Analytics.
        1. Create a separate column to show Schoology views in Screencastify analytics.
        2. If watcher is signed-in- show user name and email
        3. If watcher is not signed-in or non-google user- show as anonymous user or use “name” if available.
3. Build My Videos file picker
    1. File picker initiates when a user clicks on the ‘Screencastify’ app in Schoology in ‘Add Material’ or through Content Editor ‘**APP**’ plug-in.
    2. Allow double sign-in. Users will be asked to sign in to Screencastify.
        1. Update Google Auth to save the sign-in information
    3. If user doesn’t have an account with SC (new user), allow account creation through google sign-in
    4. Opens an embedded My Videos file picker in iframe
        1. Update our app and allow it to be used in an iFrame (see `X-Frame-Options`)
        2. If the users have one or more videos in “My Videos”;
            1. User can select only one video at a time 
        3. If the users have no video in the “My Videos” (zero state)
            1. Show users existing zero-state messaging (start recording in 3 steps)
            2. Clicking on the link will take them to CWS if we detect no extension downloaded or quick start guide if extension is downloaded.
        4. If a video is locked due to freemium limitations, disallow selecting the video.
        5. If a user picks a video that has share settings as ‘private’, we automatically change it to “Anyone with link” and watchers will be captured as ‘anonymous” in analytics.
        6. Notify users about the change to share settings on ‘preview’ iframe. (See yellow banner in wireframes)
    5. Users must be able to preview the video on an iframe screen.
        1. Full video must be playable
        2. Preview screen must offer functionality of play, pause and scrubber in video player.  
        3. Preview screen must have two options: `Back` and `Share`
            1. `Back` button brings user back to ‘My Video’ picker screen. Users can select another video if they need to.
            2. `Share` button enables proceeding with the workflow with the selected video.
        4. **App** video (watch page) gets embedded within Schoology UI for student users to view.
    
    4.  Screencastify can collect analytics on views coming from Schoology
    
    **Student-User Experience**
    
    1. Student users can view **APP** videos on Schoology
    2. If share settings of **APP** video is set to “anyone in my domain”;
        1. Show student users a sign in modal
        2. Allow student users to sign in 
        3. Allow student users to view the video post sign-in
        4. Collect student users information for analytics
    3. If share settings of ***APP*** video is set to “anyone with link”;
        1. Show student users a modal to input “name”
        2. Student users must click “continue” to save the name and proceed with video viewing
        3. Collect student user’s information and name for Analytics

jobs.title: Build a solution to a complex staff rostering
jobs.description:
Staff Rostering Challenge

Hi,
I am reaching out to you with a unique challenge that I believe your expertise could greatly assist me with. 
In my role, I am responsible for rostering approximately 130 individuals on a 4-week basis, where each cycle spans 28 days. The complexity of this task arises from the numerous variables and constraints involved in creating an efficient and fair schedule:

1. **Daily Slots**: There are 36 different slots to fill each day, varying in terms of start times and locations.

2. **Staff Constraints**: Some staff members cannot work in specific places or during certain times due to their personal preferences or restrictions.

3. **Full-time vs. Part-time**: Among the 130 individuals, 80 are full-time staff members who must work ten days every fortnight, with an exception allowing 9 days in one of the two fortnights within the 28-day cycle.

4. **Night Shifts**: Staff members working night shifts require a mandatory two-day break after their last night shift.

5. **Preferred Work Patterns**: Ideally, we aim to provide full-time staff members with 5 days in a row and a maximum of 6 days in a row, considering their availability and preferences.

Given the intricate nature of this problem, I have developed a rudimentary Excel sheet to assist in creating schedules. However, it falls short of efficiently managing the vast array of variables and constraints at play.

I am seeking your assistance to develop a software solution that can streamline the rostering process. Ideally, this program should allow me to input the availability, preferences, and constraints of staff members for each month, while taking into account the rules and variables that govern our scheduling. The ultimate goal is to generate rosters that are both optimized and tailored to meet the needs of our diverse workforce.

I believe that your expertise in software development, particularly in the realm of creating algorithms and systems to solve complex problems, could be instrumental in addressing this challenge.
If you are interested in exploring this opportunity further or would like to see the Excel sheet I've been using as a starting point, please let me know. I would greatly appreciate the opportunity to discuss this matter with you in more detail and explore the feasibility of creating a robust solution.
